  "local_port": 41304,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "After 22 years my husband wants out and I believe he is seeing someone, but I am still very much in love. How do I get over him? Or win him back?",
  "response": "I\u2019m so sorry you\u2019re going through this\u2014it\u2019s incredibly painful to face the end of a long-term relationship, especially when you\u2019re still deeply in love. Here are some steps to help you navigate this challenging time, whether your goal is to move on or to work toward reconciliation:\n\n---\n\n### **If You Want to Move On**\n1. **Allow Yourself to Grieve**  \n   It\u2019s okay to feel heartbroken, angry, or confused. Give yourself permission to process these emotions. Journaling, talking to a trusted friend, or seeking therapy can help.\n\n2. **Focus on Self-Care**  \n   Prioritize your physical and emotional well-being. Exercise, eat well, get enough sleep, and engage in activities that bring you joy or relaxation.\n\n3. **Set Boundaries**  \n   If your husband is seeing someone else, it\u2019s important to protect your heart. Consider limiting contact or setting clear boundaries to avoid unnecessary pain.\n\n4. **Reconnect with Yourself**  \n   Rediscover who you are outside of the relationship. Pursue hobbies, interests, or goals you may have put on hold. This can help rebuild your sense of identity and self-worth.\n\n5. **Seek Support**  \n   Lean on friends, family, or a support group. A therapist can also provide guidance and help you process your emotions in a healthy way.\n\n6. **Give It Time**  \n   Healing is a process, and it won\u2019t happen overnight. Be patient with yourself as you navigate this new chapter.\n\n---\n\n### **If You Want to Win Him Back**\n1. **Assess the Situation**  \n   Before taking action, reflect on why your husband wants out. Is this a temporary crisis, or has the relationship been struggling for a while? Understanding the root cause is essential.\n\n2. **Communicate Openly and Calmly**  \n   Express your feelings honestly, but avoid blaming or pressuring him. Ask if he\u2019s willing to discuss the issues and work on the relationship together.\n\n3. **Focus on Personal Growth**  \n   Sometimes, working on yourself can reignite your partner\u2019s interest. Show him the best version of yourself\u2014confident, independent, and emotionally stable.\n\n4. **Suggest Couples Therapy**  \n   If he\u2019s open to it, therapy can provide a safe space to address underlying issues and improve communication.\n\n5. **Give Him Space**  \n   If he\u2019s feeling overwhelmed, pushing too hard may push him further away. Respect his need for space while remaining open to reconciliation.\n\n6. **Prepare for the Possibility of Letting Go**  \n   Sometimes, despite your best efforts, the relationship may not work out. Be mentally prepared for this outcome and focus on your own well-being.\n\n---\n\n### **Final Thoughts**\nWhether you choose to move on or try to win him back, remember that your happiness and worth are not dependent on someone else. You deserve a relationship where both partners are fully committed and invested. Take things one day at a time, and be kind to yourself as you navigate this difficult journey.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
